      Governance, fraud, constitutions, etc.
   =20
 =20
Last week  we talked about a Twitter poll that Elon Musk did, asking if he =
should sell 10% of his Tesla stock. =E2=80=9CI will abide by the results of=
 this poll, whichever way it goes,=E2=80=9D he tweeted. I wrote some discus=
sion questions. Here were two of them:7. If Musk does not abide by the resu=
lts of this poll =E2=80=94 if he does not sell 10% of his stock, as a major=
ity of 3.5 million randos on Twitter told him to =E2=80=94 would that be se=
curities fraud? In answering this question, consider who might have been de=
frauded, and how. Consider also how much time Musk should get to abide by t=
he poll: If he sells 1% of his stock per year for 10 years, would that coun=
t?8. If your answer to Question 7 was =E2=80=9Cyes=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 i.e.,=
 if you think it would be securities fraud for Musk to tweet a poll and say=
 he=E2=80=99d abide by the result and then not do it =E2=80=94 then does th=
at mean that the Twitter poll was in fact legally binding? More generally, =
is anything that the chief executive officer of a public company says on Tw=
itter legally binding, because if it is not true then that=E2=80=99s securi=
ties fraud?For what little it=E2=80=99s worth, my answer=C2=A0to both of th=
ose questions is a very cautious =E2=80=9Cprobably?=E2=80=9D (Nothing here =
is legal advice, etc.) If I were a law professor teaching a contracts class=
 this semester, I would definitely discuss these tweets in class, and I=E2=
=80=99d add a few more lawyer-y questions. =E2=80=9CWhat happens to the doc=
trine of  consideration when anything you say on Twitter creates legally bi=
nding obligations under the law of securities fraud,=E2=80=9D would be one =
of them.I=E2=80=99ve got some more hypotheticals. For instance let=E2=80=99=
s say you buy stock from a company in a publicly registered initial public =
offering. The prospectus for the offering says, repeatedly and prominently,=
 that there is only a single class of stock and that every share gets one v=
ote. The company=E2=80=99s certificate of incorporation says that there are=
 two classes of stock, Class A, which is sold to the public in the IPO and =
gets one vote per share, and Class B, which is retained by the founder and =
gets 1,000 votes per share. After the IPO, the founder wants to do somethin=
g, the shareholders want to do something else, and the founder says =E2=80=
=9Chaha, surprise, I=E2=80=99ve got 1,000 votes for share and I=E2=80=99ll =
do what I like!=E2=80=9D Is she correct?I think as a matter of corporate la=
w =E2=80=94=C2=A0as a matter of what the certificate of incorporation says =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0sure, she is correct. But if she does anything that the othe=
r shareholders don=E2=80=99t like, they will sue her for securities fraud, =
and they will win and get piles of money in damages. Also the Securities an=
d Exchange Commission or the Justice Department might investigate her blata=
nt fraud, and she might go to prison.=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s not quite as good a=
s having the certificate of incorporation say what it=E2=80=99s supposed to=
 say. But for most practical purposes it is a good substitute. She will go =
use her 1,000 votes to amend the certificate to say what it=E2=80=99s suppo=
sed to say, because there are powerful enforcement mechanisms if she doesn=
=E2=80=99t.Or if a company issues a bond with a prospectus saying =E2=80=9C=
this bond pays 5% interest,=E2=80=9D on the cover and repeatedly throughout=
 the prospectus, but=C2=A0the indenture says =E2=80=9Cthis bond pays 3% int=
erest,=E2=80=9D and page 67 of the prospectus says =E2=80=9Cthis prospectus=
 is qualified by reference to the indenture, which actually governs the ter=
ms of the bond,=E2=80=9D what is the interest rate on the bond? I think the=
 contract-law answer is 3%, the rate in the indenture, the actual contract =
that governs the bond. I think the securities-law answer is 5%, the rate pr=
ominently displayed in the=C2=A0marketing of the bond. =E2=80=9CBut we said=
 in a cross-reference on page 67 to check with the indenture!=E2=80=9D No, =
come on. Either you pay 5% or you get sued for securities fraud and you los=
e and pay damages of, effectively, 5% interest.Incidentally neither of thes=
e hypotheticals would ever, ever, ever happen, because if you=E2=80=99re do=
ing an IPO or a bond offering you=E2=80=99ll hire lawyers, and the underwri=
ters will hire lawyers, and all the lawyers will work hard to make sure tha=
t the legal rights are properly reflected in the prospectus,[4] because the=
y are very concerned with not doing fraud. But that=E2=80=99s sort of the p=
oint.The point is that the law of=C2=A0fraud=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0here secur=
ities fraud, but more generally =E2=80=9Cwire fraud=E2=80=9D or just =E2=80=
=9Cfraud=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0creates a sort of backup to contract law, =
corporate law, partnership law, etc. If you go around telling people =E2=80=
=9Chey, sign this contract and you=E2=80=99ll get a pony,=E2=80=9D and they=
 sign the contract and it actually says =E2=80=9Cyou will never get a pony,=
=E2=80=9D they will not have much ability to sue you under the contract, bu=
t someone will probably go after you for fraud, depending on things like ho=
w many people you marketed it to and how unsophisticated they were and how =
high-pressure your marketing was and and how complicated the contract was a=
nd how much money you got out of them.People complain about this from time =
to time; in particular, it is common for fraud defendants to say =E2=80=9Ct=
his is not a case of fraud, but a simple contract dispute in which we disag=
ree with our counterparties about what our obligations were under the contr=
act.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0There is a lot of overlap between those things.I think t=
his is an interesting situation =E2=80=94=C2=A0related to but distinct from=
 =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0for, like,=
 corporate governance and Elon Musk and executives on Twitter. I think that=
 corporations and their executives are, in broad terms, obligated to do not=
 only what their contracts and corporate documents say they have to do, but=
 also what they have=C2=A0said publicly=C2=A0they are going to do (and part=
icularly what they have=C2=A0said to investors=C2=A0they are going to do),=
=C2=A0because if they do something else they=E2=80=99ll get sued for securi=
ties fraud.But I suppose it is also an interesting situation for things tha=
t don=E2=80=99t have contracts or corporate documents. We  talked a bit the=
 other day=C2=A0about ConstitutionDAO, a decentralized autonomous organizat=
ion that is raising money from crypto people to buy a copy of the U.S. Cons=
titution. (Here is  a Bloomberg News story about it.) People are interested=
 in the legal structure of this thing. Basically it seems like there is a D=
elaware limited liability company that will take ownership of the document =
(if they win the auction), and there=E2=80=99s a tax-exempt organization ca=
lled Endaoment that will act as the LLC=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cfiscal sponsor=
=E2=80=9D and actually buy the document from the auction house and hold it =
on behalf of the LLC. These are normal legal entities, and the LLC=E2=80=99=
s members =E2=80=94=C2=A0in effect, the legal owners =E2=80=94=C2=A0are som=
e of the humans who have promoted the DAO.But the DAO itself is a decentral=
ized autonomous organization, a blockchain thing with governance tokens tha=
t can vote on what the DAO will do and smart contracts to aggregate those v=
otes. And the connection between the DAO and the LLC is a little vague:The =
LLC is currently legally owned by DAO community members Alice Ma and Julian=
 Weisser, who are representing the wider DAO community for this agreement. =
The DAO will advise the LLC owners on all actions taken. This structure is =
intended to be temporary and can be changed according to the DAO community=
=E2=80=99s wishes after the auction is complete.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CAdvise.=E2=
=80=9D You can vote your governance tokens in the DAO, and then the two par=
ticular humans who run the LLC that owns the copy of the Constitution will =
take your votes under advisement. It=E2=80=99s not quite the sort of trustl=
ess decentralized blah blah blah that crypto promises.So what=E2=80=99s to =
stop those two humans from running off with the money, or the Constitution?=
[5] The answer=C2=A0absolutely cannot be=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe immutable code o=
f a smart contract on the blockchain,=E2=80=9D because the Constitution is =
a piece of paper (parchment? whatever) that does not live on the blockchain=
, and a smart contract cannot stop someone from pocketing it and walking aw=
ay. (And since the money for the purchase needs to be in dollars in a dumb =
old bank account, the smart contract probably can=E2=80=99t stop someone fr=
om stealing it either.)=C2=A0Conceivably the answer is =E2=80=9Cthe DAO is =
actually a limited liability company under Delaware law, and the LLC agreem=
ent and Delaware law constrain the members of the LLC to do what the DAO sa=
ys.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s not clear to me whether or not this is the case. =
It is tricky to do that, but a lot of lawyers are very much working on thin=
gs like this, mechanisms to integrate DAOs and crypto-token voting into tra=
ditional business-entity and contract law. (Wyoming has a =E2=80=9CDAO LLC=
=E2=80=9D legal entity, though ConstitutionDAO chose not to use it.) Eventu=
ally one assumes that a world of crypto companies will have to operate like=
 this: There will be smart contracts on the blockchain, and legal entities =
that carry out the smart contracts=E2=80=99 desires in the real world,=C2=
=A0and there will be well-understood interfaces between them, and statutes =
and case law that allow the smart contracts to govern the entities and so f=
orth.But right now I suspect the main=C2=A0legal answer is the backup answe=
r[6]: If they pocket the money, that sure looks like=C2=A0wire fraud, and t=
he DAO investors can probably sue for fraud and also probably get prosecuto=
rs interested. The enforcement mechanism is: =E2=80=9CIf you market a thing=
 with=C2=A0promises, and raise a lot of money from strangers based on those=
 promises, you=E2=80=99d better try hard to do what you promised or you=E2=
=80=99ll get in trouble for fraud.=E2=80=9D Not always! In particular, if y=
ou are ripping people off=C2=A0on the blockchain, there=E2=80=99s a decent =
chance that courts and prosecutors will laugh at your victims rather than t=
hrowing the book at you.=C2=A0But=C2=A0if you raise enough money in a high-=
profile enough way, you should probably try to do what you say you=E2=80=99=
ll do.
