<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p><table class=3D"header" =
width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Zillow</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the one hand, sure, I can see why s=
omeone might consider this a problem:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">When executives at Zillow Group Inc. pored over the company=E2=80=99=
s earnings in the spring, they saw a problem: The real-estate firm was maki=
ng too much money.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the othe=
r hand, it does feel like a problem that I would happily take off Zillow=E2=
=80=99s hands? There are worse problems than making too much money! Making =
too little money is a worse problem, for instance. Losing money. These are =
the problems. Making too much money is just interesting.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">That was=C2=A0the first sentence of <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25751507.256650/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9=
hcnRpY2xlcy96aWxsb3ctb2ZmZXJzLXJlYWwtZXN0YXRlLWFsZ29yaXRobS1ob21lcy1pYnV5ZX=
ItMTE2MzcxNTkyNjE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBad887c76" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the Wall Stree=
t Journal=E2=80=99s postmortem</a> about how Zillow ended up=C2=A0<em>losin=
g</em> a bunch of money buying and flipping houses and had to shut down tha=
t business. The problem was that =E2=80=9Cthe company=E2=80=99s algorithm, =
which was supposed to predict housing prices, didn=E2=80=99t seem to unders=
tand the market,=E2=80=9D and was generating prices that were too low.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This had two effects. First, most people declin=
ed its offers, which were too low: =E2=80=9COnly 10% of people who asked fo=
r a Zillow offer and eventually sold their home ended up selling it to Zill=
ow,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CZillow was also behind on its target for home pur=
chases=E2=80=9D in the first quarter.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Second, when people=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>accept Zillow=E2=80=99s offers =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0because they were in a hurry, or didn=E2=80=99t have a good =
sense of the market =E2=80=94=C2=A0Zillow made a ton of money:</p><blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The first quarter delivered home-sale profi=
ts that were more than twice as high as anticipated, the company said. Zill=
ow expected to make money primarily from transaction fees and from services=
 such as title insurance=E2=80=94not from making a killing on the flip.=C2=
=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Zillow executives looked a=
t this state of affairs and said, well, this state of affairs is bad, we ne=
ed to grow our market share and make our algorithms more accurate. We are l=
ooking to be a first-choice <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/25751507.256650/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fyd=
GljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTEtMDMvemlsbG93LWlzLWRvbmUtdHJhZGluZy1ob3VzZXM_Y21waWQ9QkJE=
MTExODIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXI=
mdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMTE4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB55d99162" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;"> market maker in home-selling</a>, and we can=E2=80=
=99t do that if our prices are too low. So they tweaked the algorithms to g=
enerate=C2=A0<em>higher=C2=A0</em>prices. Those prices also turned out not =
to be particularly accurate, but in the other direction. If you systematica=
lly bid too low, you will not do many trades, but you will make a lot of mo=
ney on each trade. If you systematically bid too high, you will lose money =
on each trade, and=C2=A0<em>also you will do a whole ton of trades</em>. Th=
is is much worse.[1]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine bein=
g in that meeting and saying,=C2=A0hang on a minute, are we sure about this=
? Sure,=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0bad that our algorithms are inaccurate, and =
it would be better if they were more accurate. But that seems hard. We have=
 smart people working to make them accurate, and so far they have failed. I=
f we tweak the algorithms=C2=A0to generate higher prices, that may just mak=
e them inaccurate in the much worse direction.[2] On the other hand right n=
ow we have a business that buys houses at below-market prices, flips them, =
and makes a big profit on each one. A lot of people would like to have a bu=
siness like that! Sure it would be better if we could do=C2=A0<em>more </em=
>trades like that, but you=E2=80=99re realistically not going to find tens =
of thousands of people who will sell you their homes for below market value=
. But we have found thousands! That=E2=80=99s pretty good!</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know, it=E2=80=99s a weird story about tech=
nology and scale, about how many businesses =E2=80=94=C2=A0in particular, m=
any public companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0aim to maximize not <em>profit </em>but=
 <em>size</em>. In concept, a business model like =E2=80=9Csend everyone in=
 America a bid on their house that is too low, and then buy the houses from=
 the minority of suckers who take your bid=E2=80=9D seems =E2=80=A6=C2=A0ob=
viously =E2=80=A6=C2=A0lucrative?[3] Like, I would be happy to do that busi=
ness? I don=E2=80=99t have the capital for it, but I=E2=80=99m sure there a=
re hedge funds who would do this business if they could.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">But the only way to actually do it =E2=80=94=C2=A0to generate=
 millions of plausible-but-too-low=C2=A0bids, and to get them in front of p=
otential sellers =E2=80=94=C2=A0is to have the scale and reach and technolo=
gy of a big online home-information company like Zillow. And once you=E2=80=
=99re at that scale, doing a few thousand dumb lucrative transactions almos=
t isn=E2=80=99t worth it for you; the only way to justify it is to scale it=
 up until it=E2=80=99s larger, smarter and less lucrative. (Or, in Zillow=
=E2=80=99s case, larger, equally dumb and disastrous.)</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">Also you probably got to that scale by being a popular trusted =
source for home information, which is valuable for your main business of se=
lling ads on the internet;=C2=A0sending people lowball bids to try to sucke=
r them into selling to you might not be great for that business. As <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25751507.256650/aHR0cHM6L=
y9zdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5jb20vMjAyMS96aWxsb3ctc2h1dHMtZG93bi1vZmZlcnMtd2hlcmUtemls=
bG93LXdlbnQtd3JvbmctcmVmbGVjdGluZy1vbi16aWxsb3ctYWdncmVnYXRpb24tYW5kLWludGV=
ncmF0aW9uLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2ea4a291" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Ben Thompson wrote</=
a>: =E2=80=9CBecause the company felt compelled to push Offers, it was actu=
ally leaving most potential sellers with a bad taste in their mouth; this i=
s a big problem given that an Aggregator=E2=80=99s advantage is the fact th=
e end users like it and go there first.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">And so Zillow could not do this business model, because the business =
was too small for Zillow. And I could not do this business model, because I=
 am too small for the business. But for a little while, it was kind of a go=
od business!</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"auto=
