; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> we talked about</a> a Twitter poll tha=
t Elon Musk did, asking if he should sell 10% of his Tesla stock. =E2=80=9C=
I will abide by the results of this poll, whichever way it goes,=E2=80=9D h=
e tweeted. I wrote some discussion questions. Here were two of them:</p><bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">7. If Musk does not abide by the resu=
lts of this poll =E2=80=94 if he does not sell 10% of his stock, as a major=
ity of 3.5 million randos on Twitter told him to =E2=80=94 would that be se=
curities fraud? In answering this question, consider who might have been de=
frauded, and how. Consider also how much time Musk should get to abide by t=
he poll: If he sells 1% of his stock per year for 10 years, would that coun=
t?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">8. If your answer to Question 7 was =E2=
=80=9Cyes=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 i.e., if you think it would be securities frau=
d for Musk to tweet a poll and say he=E2=80=99d abide by the result and the=
n not do it =E2=80=94 then does that mean that the Twitter poll was in fact=
 legally binding? More generally, is anything that the chief executive offi=
cer of a public company says on Twitter legally binding, because if it is n=
ot true then that=E2=80=99s securities fraud?</p></blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">For what little it=E2=80=99s worth, my answer=C2=A0to both =
of those questions is a very cautious =E2=80=9Cprobably?=E2=80=9D (Nothing =
here is legal advice, etc.) If I were a law professor teaching a contracts =
class this semester, I would definitely discuss these tweets in class, and =
I=E2=80=99d add a few more lawyer-y questions. =E2=80=9CWhat happens to the=
 doctrine of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25751=
507.256650/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEt=
