gmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC42ecae24" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
"> consideration</a> when anything you say on Twitter creates legally bindi=
ng obligations under the law of securities fraud,=E2=80=9D would be one of =
them.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=E2=80=99ve got some more hypothetic=
als. For instance let=E2=80=99s say you buy stock from a company in a publi=
cly registered initial public offering. The prospectus for the offering say=
s, repeatedly and prominently, that there is only a single class of stock a=
nd that every share gets one vote. The company=E2=80=99s certificate of inc=
orporation says that there are two classes of stock, Class A, which is sold=
 to the public in the IPO and gets one vote per share, and Class B, which i=
s retained by the founder and gets 1,000 votes per share. After the IPO, th=
e founder wants to do something, the shareholders want to do something else=
, and the founder says =E2=80=9Chaha, surprise, I=E2=80=99ve got 1,000 vote=
s for share and I=E2=80=99ll do what I like!=E2=80=9D Is she correct?</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think as a matter of corporate law =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0as a matter of what the certificate of incorporation says =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0sure, she is correct. But if she does anything that the other shareho=
lders don=E2=80=99t like, they will sue her for securities fraud, and they =
will win and get piles of money in damages. Also the Securities and Exchang=
e Commission or the Justice Department might investigate her blatant fraud,=
 and she might go to prison.=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s not quite as good as having =
the certificate of incorporation say what it=E2=80=99s supposed to say. But=
 for most practical purposes it is a good substitute. She will go use her 1=
,000 votes to amend the certificate to say what it=E2=80=99s supposed to sa=
y, because there are powerful enforcement mechanisms if she doesn=E2=80=99t=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or if a company issues a bond with a pros=
pectus saying =E2=80=9Cthis bond pays 5% interest,=E2=80=9D on the cover an=
d repeatedly throughout the prospectus, but=C2=A0the indenture says =E2=80=
=9Cthis bond pays 3% interest,=E2=80=9D and page 67 of the prospectus says =
=E2=80=9Cthis prospectus is qualified by reference to the indenture, which =
actually governs the terms of the bond,=E2=80=9D what is the interest rate =
on the bond? I think the contract-law answer is 3%, the rate in the indentu=
re, the actual contract that governs the bond. I think the securities-law a=
nswer is 5%, the rate prominently displayed in the=C2=A0marketing of the bo=
nd. =E2=80=9CBut we said in a cross-reference on page 67 to check with the =
indenture!=E2=80=9D No, come on. Either you pay 5% or you get sued for secu=
rities fraud and you lose and pay damages of, effectively, 5% interest.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incidentally neither of these hypotheticals wo=
uld ever, ever, ever happen, because if you=E2=80=99re doing an IPO or a bo=
nd offering you=E2=80=99ll hire lawyers, and the underwriters will hire law=
yers, and all the lawyers will work hard to make sure that the legal rights=
 are properly reflected in the prospectus,[4] because they are very concern=
ed with not doing fraud. But that=E2=80=99s sort of the point.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point is that the law of=C2=A0<em>fraud=C2=A0</em>=
=E2=80=94=C2=A0here securities fraud, but more generally =E2=80=9Cwire frau=
d=E2=80=9D or just =E2=80=9Cfraud=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0creates a sort of=
 backup to contract law, corporate law, partnership law, etc. If you go aro=
und telling people =E2=80=9Chey, sign this contract and you=E2=80=99ll get =
a pony,=E2=80=9D and they sign the contract and it actually says =E2=80=9Cy=
ou will never get a pony,=E2=80=9D they will not have much ability to sue y=
ou under the contract, but someone will probably go after you for fraud, de=
pending on things like how many people you marketed it to and how unsophist=
icated they were and how high-pressure your marketing was and and how compl=
icated the contract was and how much money you got out of them.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People complain about this from time to time; in parti=
cular, it is common for fraud defendants to say =E2=80=9Cthis is not a case=
 of fraud, but a simple contract dispute in which we disagree with our coun=
terparties about what our obligations were under the contract.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0There is a lot of overlap between those things.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">I think this is an interesting situation =E2=80=94=C2=A0related to =
but distinct from =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/25751507.256650/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydG=
